function findLengthOfShortestSubarray(arr) {
    const n = arr.length;
    let left = 0, right = n - 1;
    while (left < n - 1 && arr[left] <= arr[left + 1]) left++;
    if (left === n - 1) return 0;
    while (right > 0 && arr[right] >= arr[right - 1]) right--;
    let result = Math.min(n - left - 1, right);
    let i = 0, j = right;
    while (i <= left && j < n) {
        if (arr[i] <= arr[j]) {
            result = Math.min(result, j - i - 1);
            i++;
        } else {
            j++;
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

    The algorithm starts by finding the longest non-decreasing subarray from both ends (left and right) of the array. If the left index reaches the end of the array, it means the array is already non-decreasing and we can return 0.

Then, we initialize the result as the minimum of the remaining subarray lengths on the left side and the right side. We use two pointers i and j starting from the left index and the right index, respectively.

We iterate through the array and compare the values of arr[i] and arr[j]. If arr[i] <= arr[j], it means the subarray from i to j can be non-decreasing, so we update the result with the minimum length of this subarray. If arr[i] > arr[j], we increment j.

When the loop finishes, the result is the length of the shortest subarray to remove to make the remaining elements non-decreasing.

